Linux Learning Roadmap Explained (Visual Notes Style)
1️⃣ Beginner Level – Foundations

Goal: Understand Linux, navigate filesystem, basic commands, files, permissions.

A. Introduction

Linux = Kernel + OS + Tools

Diagram: Linux Overview

+--------------------------+
|       Applications       |  <- Browsers, Editors, Programs
+--------------------------+
|        Shell/CLI         |  <- Command Line (Terminal)
+--------------------------+
|      Linux Kernel        |  <- Core OS: handles CPU, memory, devices
+--------------------------+
|      Hardware Layer      |  <- CPU, RAM, HDD, Network
+--------------------------+

Popular Linux Distros (Operating Systems)

Ubuntu ──> Beginner Friendly
Debian ──> Stable, server use
CentOS / AlmaLinux ──> Enterprise
Fedora ──> Cutting-edge

Filesystem Hierarchy Visual

/        -> Root directory
├── /home  -> Users’ files
├── /etc   -> Configuration files
├── /var   -> Variable data (logs, databases)
├── /usr   -> Applications, binaries
├── /bin   -> Basic commands like ls, cp
└── /tmp   -> Temporary files
B. Basic Commands

Navigation

pwd       -> Show current directory
ls        -> List files (ls -l for details)
cd        -> Change directory

File Operations

touch file.txt      -> Create empty file
mkdir folder        -> Create directory
cp file1 file2      -> Copy file
mv file1 folder/    -> Move file
rm file             -> Delete file
cat file            -> View file content
more / less file    -> Scroll through file

System Info

uname -a   -> Kernel & OS info
whoami     -> Current user
hostname   -> Computer name
date       -> Show date/time
uptime     -> How long system is running

Disk Usage

df -h      -> Disk space
du -sh dir -> Folder size
C. File Permissions
-rwxr-xr--  1 user group 123 Mar 24 file.txt
|  |  |  |
|  |  |  -> Others permissions (r=read, w=write, x=execute)
|  |  -> Group permissions
|  -> Owner permissions
-> File type (- file, d directory)

Commands:

chmod 755 file    -> Change permissions
chown user file   -> Change owner
chgrp group file  -> Change group
D. Text Editors
nano – Simple, beginner-friendly
vim – Powerful, modal editor (i=insert, :wq=save & exit)
E. Package Management
apt update        -> Refresh repo list
apt install pkg   -> Install package
apt remove pkg    -> Remove package
apt search pkg    -> Search package
F. Hands-on Labs
Create a directory structure:
mkdir -p ~/projects/test
touch ~/projects/test/file1.txt
Move, copy, delete files
Change file permissions
Install and remove a package: sudo apt install tree
2️⃣ Intermediate Level – Shell, Networking & Scripting

Goal: Automate tasks, manage users, understand processes and networking.

A. Shell Utilities
grep 'error' file.log      -> Search for 'error'
awk '{print $2}' file      -> Extract column
sed 's/old/new/' file      -> Replace text
cut -d ' ' -f2 file        -> Get column
sort file                  -> Sort lines
uniq file                  -> Remove duplicates
head file                  -> First 10 lines
tail file                  -> Last 10 lines

Pipes & Redirection

cat file | grep 'error' > error.log
B. Processes & Services
ps aux        -> List processes
top / htop    -> Monitor CPU/memory
kill PID      -> Kill process
systemctl start nginx
systemctl stop nginx
C. Users & Groups
useradd john
usermod -aG sudo john
passwd john
groupadd devs
D. Networking
ping google.com
traceroute google.com
netstat -tulnp
ip addr
ifconfig
scp file user@server:/path
rsync -av folder/ user@server:/path
wget URL
curl URL
E. Bash Scripting

Example: Backup script

#!/bin/bash
# backup.sh
SRC=~/projects
DEST=~/backup
mkdir -p $DEST
cp -r $SRC/* $DEST/
echo "Backup complete!"

Run: bash backup.sh

Hands-on Labs
Write scripts to backup folders
Transfer files between VMs with scp
Monitor CPU/memory and log to file
3️⃣ Advanced Level – System Administration & Security

Goal: Administer servers, logs, services, security, containers.

A. Filesystem & Storage
lsblk             -> List disks
fdisk /dev/sda    -> Partition disk
mount /dev/sda1 /mnt
umount /mnt
df -h
du -sh /var

LVM (Logical Volume Management)

pvcreate /dev/sdb
vgcreate vg1 /dev/sdb
lvcreate -n lv1 -L 10G vg1
mkfs.ext4 /dev/vg1/lv1
mount /dev/vg1/lv1 /mnt/data
B. Logs & Monitoring
journalctl -xe
tail -f /var/log/syslog
vmstat 1
iostat -x
sar -u 1 5
C. Networking & Security
ufw enable
ufw allow 22
iptables -L
ssh-keygen
nmap 192.168.1.1
D. Services
systemctl start apache2
systemctl enable nginx
systemctl status mysql
E. Virtualization & Containers
Docker: docker run -it ubuntu bash
LXC/LXD: Create containers
VirtualBox/KVM: Run multiple VMs
Hands-on Labs
Setup Apache/Nginx
SSH key authentication
Cron jobs for automated backups
Dockerize an app
4️⃣ Expert Level – Linux Mastery

Goal: Deep system internals, kernel, networking, security, cloud Linux.

Topics

Kernel compilation: make menuconfig && make && make install
Network services: DNS, DHCP, FTP, NFS, Samba
High availability / clustering
Troubleshooting: strace, lsof, tcpdump, perf
Security: firewall, fail2ban, auditd, AppArmor/SELinux
CI/CD: Jenkins, GitLab Runner
Cloud: AWS EC2 Linux, Azure Linux VM, GCP
